Some more reference material: ÔªøÔªøÔªøÔªøÔªøÔªøÔªø1962 (Series SY1-L, M, H) 1962 Imperial Custom Southampton two-door 1962 Imperial Crown convertible The tailfins were largely truncated in 1962, topped with free-standing gunsight taillights, but these were elongated and streamlined. The front grille was split, as was on the 1955 and 1956 models, and a large round eagle hood ornament was fitted for the first time. The 1962 models had a new, slimmer TorqueFlite A727 automatic transmission, which allowed a smaller transmission "hump" in the floor. This provided greater comfort for middle front-seat passengers. Dual exhaust were only standard on convertibles. 1962 also marked the closing of Imperial's dedicated assembly plant. All later Imperials were once again built in the same Jefferson Avenue facilities in Detroit as Chryslers, as sales were insufficient to maintain a separate facility. 1962 production totaled 14,337. Shortly before leaving Chrysler, Virgil Exner had planned for a smaller Imperial to go along with the downsized 1962 Mopars, but the idea never went anywhere.

Overall Condition is excellent.................................Something just found out. When the Tahoe had 120k miles on it I signed up for a warranty through a company called Carshield. When I signed up the payment to warranty the Drive Train cost $79 per month. It only covers the drivetrain, but it has paid for itself. The warranty covers repairs 100% after a $100 deductible, per occurrence. When I had the new transmission put in I had it done at Reliable Chevrolet in Richardson and it was paid for 100%, with the exception, of the deductible. With 154k miles on the vehicle, that same warranty would now cost $170 per month. I called Carshield yesterday and just found out that the original warranty I started is assumable by the new owner, should I sell the vehicle, and it is assumable at the $79 premium I have been paying. The warranty is month to month with no contracted length. In other words, a new owner can assume the $79 payment for as long as they want or as long as they own the vehicle and know that any issues with the Drivetrain will be covered with a $100 deductible. New buyer can keep the warranty as long as they pay the premium each month and yet drop it anytime without any consequences should they no longer want the coverage it affords.

Noteworthy: New tires n refreshed like new rims New injectors New coil packs New fuel pressure regulator New brakes all around Many other new parts Over $1800 or more in tuneup parts etc. Summary: The 1999 Nissan Maxima 3.0, often referred to as the "four-door sports car" is considered one of the last true Japanese sedans with a focus on driving dynamics and durability before the rise of more "fuel-efficient" but sometimes less engaging models plagued with more sensors and new issues. . The 1999 Maxima is particularly sought after for several reasons: 1. Solid Engine & Performance: The 3.0L V6 engine (VG30DE) produced around 190 hp, which was respectable at the time and offered a good balance of power and reliability. It's known for being a strong, long-lasting engine when properly maintained. 2. Durability: The Nissan Maxima was well-regarded for its build quality. The combination of solid engineering, reliable components, and Nissan's overall reputation for longevity made this model especially durable, with many still on the road today with high mileage. 3. Comfort & Practicality: With spacious interiors and a decent list of features for the time, it was a good daily driver with a comfortable ride, solid handling, and a good mix of luxury without being too fancy or expensive to maintain. 4. The End of an Era: The 1999 Maxima marked the end of the "Old School"Nissan design and engineering before the company started shifting to more mainstream, eco-focused models. This makes it a kind of a Golden Age model for those who remember when Japanese cars had more enthusiast appeal and a focus on durability. 5. No CVT: Unlike the newer Maxima models after 2005, which have switched to continuously variable transmissions (CVTs), the 1999 model uses a traditional 4-speed automatic so you can avoid the myriad of troubles servicing them and spending a fortune to put a new one in since they can't be rebuilt. Traditional Gears over a CVT band that just "goes out" Finally: That blend of performance, old school reliability from the glory days of Japanese automotive engineering makes the 1999 Nissan Maxima 3.0 a sought-after classic for car lovers

Information about the incredible W126 Mercedes Benz: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_W126 The Mercedes-Benz W126 is a series of S-Class automobiles manufactured by Mercedes-Benz between 1979 and 1992. Premiering in September 1979 as the successor to the W116 line, the W126 was the second generation to officially bear that prestigious designation, an abbreviation for the German Sonderklasse or "special class." It introduced many Mercedes-Benz safety innovations, including the first seatbelt pretensioners. The W126's twelve-year production run between 1979 and 1991 was the longest of any S-Class generation since that designation began to be used by the company in the 1970s, an homage to the first "S" designated top-class models, the mid-1950s 300 S and 300 Sc.
